&quot;The graph shows what happened when the Fed got seriously &quot;behind the curve&quot; in 1974–75. The real rate and inflation moved in opposite directions, very much like today.   

Look at the two dotted lines. In early 1975, core inflation was running at 12 percent and the real policy rate was equal to about −6 percent, a gap of about 17 percent. Today, core inflation is running at 6 percent and the real policy rate is equal to −6 percent, a gap of 12 percent—smaller than in 1975, but still strikingly large.&quot;
